WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:02.915
- And history will show,

00:00:02.915 --> 00:00:05.740
that your contribution to physical culture

00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:10.290
by coming up with the
X3 bar is well deserved,

00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:13.660
so before we start telling people about

00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:18.141
X3 bar and I'm gonna tell
everybody something right now,

00:00:18.141 --> 00:00:21.699
you have to be open minded
when we start talking

00:00:21.699 --> 00:00:23.580
about this because you're gonna think

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:25.690
you know what this is and you don't.

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:27.753
How did you come up with this?

00:00:27.753 --> 00:00:30.020
What was the deal behind it?

00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:33.900
- So my background is in
bone density research.

00:00:33.900 --> 00:00:36.783
I invented a device that
puts axial compression,

00:00:36.783 --> 00:00:39.830
so this is the axis of bone,

00:00:39.830 --> 00:00:41.183
the length of the bone,

00:00:41.183 --> 00:00:45.390
and we put force through
that bone in positions

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:48.744
where we would naturally
absorb high impact forces

00:00:48.744 --> 00:00:50.250
so you trip and fall,

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:51.115
you protect yourself.

00:00:51.115 --> 00:00:52.951
The big issue here.

00:00:52.951 --> 00:00:55.970
If I look at what people can do

00:00:57.340 --> 00:00:59.470
with full range of motion,

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:03.450
which means you're limited by
your weaker range of motion

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:05.880
hence why we call it the weaker range.

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:08.161
So studies on bench press, sticking point,

00:01:08.161 --> 00:01:10.400
this is all part of the same,

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:11.980
the same discussion.

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:14.540
So when we look at that

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:16.962
and then we look at what
a human is capable of,

00:01:16.962 --> 00:01:19.780
at extension so like
when I'm on a bench press

00:01:19.780 --> 00:01:21.383
when my arm is out here,

00:01:21.383 --> 00:01:23.069
what am I capable of

00:01:23.069 --> 00:01:27.253
with a 120 degree angle of
inclusion upper low arm,

00:01:27.253 --> 00:01:28.930
is incredible.

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:30.814
It's actually seven times greater than

00:01:30.814 --> 00:01:33.966
what I'm capable of in a
weaker range of motion.

00:01:33.966 --> 00:01:36.630
So I'm looking at this and I'm thinking,

00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:39.255
we're missing out.

00:01:39.255 --> 00:01:42.750
We are leaving the games at the gym,

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:44.528
we're not getting it.

00:01:44.528 --> 00:01:46.270
- But in.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:48.200
- Or anything like that I lifted,

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:49.740
never really got much results out of it,

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.114
I was pretty average guy,

00:01:51.114 --> 00:01:54.746
and then I started reading
about west side barbell

00:01:54.746 --> 00:01:57.863
and how you would add bands and chains

00:01:57.863 --> 00:02:01.585
to some of their lifts and
then there was a great study

00:02:01.585 --> 00:02:05.180
done by Professor Anderson
with Cornell Athletes

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.330
and they divide the athletes
in the two different groups.

00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:08.950
One group did,

00:02:08.950 --> 00:02:12.251
they used less resistance
than they would normally use

00:02:12.251 --> 00:02:13.960
and then added bands,

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.320
so let's say they had X weight here,

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:17.870
and then add extension let's say,

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:20.135
1.2x or 1.3x.

00:02:20.135 --> 00:02:22.840
So hyper loading the strong range

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:24.650
and offloading the weak range,

00:02:24.650 --> 00:02:26.648
they grew three times
the amount of muscle,

00:02:26.648 --> 00:02:28.280
I should say strength,

00:02:28.280 --> 00:02:29.770
I mean muscle is strength all together,

00:02:29.770 --> 00:02:31.780
but three times the amount of strength

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:34.380
in a given period of time
compared to the control group

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:35.885
who's is just doing their regular training

00:02:35.885 --> 00:02:37.315
tested pre to post.

00:02:37.315 --> 00:02:39.492
So ultimately,

00:02:39.492 --> 00:02:42.221
I look at both groups
who are lifting weights.

00:02:42.221 --> 00:02:43.925
The difference is,

00:02:43.925 --> 00:02:46.870
one group added bands,

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:49.630
so and I take that and
this is another thing,

00:02:49.630 --> 00:02:51.990
'cause people will look
at the science of X3

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.140
and go, well, it's not this,

00:02:54.140 --> 00:02:56.270
and they pull one
sentence out of one study

00:02:56.270 --> 00:02:58.870
and they don't know how to
read scientific documentation

00:02:58.870 --> 00:03:01.320
because there's a reason I
have multiple references,

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:03.540
it's because I'm pulling
things from different places,

00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:06.250
so then when you look at
my research out of London

00:03:06.250 --> 00:03:09.796
and you take the two
and you cross observe,

00:03:09.796 --> 00:03:12.081
forget the weight,

00:03:12.081 --> 00:03:13.993
we need more variance.

00:03:13.993 --> 00:03:15.701
- Yes.

00:03:15.701 --> 00:03:17.183
- It's actually.

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:20.320
I still want to stay strong,

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:21.800
but we alwyays talk about, oh,

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:23.060
I want to train smarter,

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:24.410
you wanna train smarter,

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:26.470
it's called the X3 bar.

00:03:26.470 --> 00:03:29.117
Because you can be as strong as you want

00:03:29.117 --> 00:03:31.770
but in the weak places

00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:33.563
where you normally injure yourself,

00:03:33.563 --> 00:03:35.339
it's dynamic for you.

00:03:35.339 --> 00:03:37.901
- Yeah, the weight drops
off where you're at risk.

00:03:37.901 --> 00:03:39.220
- It's so beautiful.

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:41.630
- And it's so, so very quickly,

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:44.688
so it comes with the 12 week program,

00:03:44.688 --> 00:03:47.330
I think on week three,

00:03:47.330 --> 00:03:49.930
I don't remember, I filmed
it a couple of weeks ago,

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:52.290
well more than 12 weeks ago.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:53.123
So the,

00:03:54.450 --> 00:03:58.530
we get into what's called
diminishing range of fatigue,

00:03:58.530 --> 00:04:00.200
so you do however many reps you do,

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.506
and then you go to fatigue
in the strong range,

00:04:02.506 --> 00:04:05.984
and then you ratchet back
and do reps in the mid range,

00:04:05.984 --> 00:04:08.590
'cause you can't get to
the strong range anymore,

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:10.120
'cause it's a very high weight.

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:11.420
- Oh interesting.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:12.253
- Yeah,

00:04:12.253 --> 00:04:13.086
and then you--

00:04:13.086 --> 00:04:14.783
- So you actually take it,

00:04:14.783 --> 00:04:17.675
you actually take the muscle
to several levels of failure.

00:04:17.675 --> 00:04:19.717
- In one set.

00:04:19.717 --> 00:04:20.979
- In one set, yeah.

00:04:20.979 --> 00:04:24.010
- So you're not letting
a massive amount of blood

00:04:24.010 --> 00:04:25.910
in to recover 'cause
the problem with pausing

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:27.300
if you're doing the board press,

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:29.261
you pause and your body
immediately starts to recover

00:04:29.261 --> 00:04:30.300
from that.

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:31.133
- Right.

00:04:31.133 --> 00:04:33.891
- So it's really not as
intense an experience

00:04:33.891 --> 00:04:35.154
as this is.

00:04:35.154 --> 00:04:38.670
This is absolute fatigue
of the muscle in all ranges

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:40.390
of motion simultaneously.

00:04:40.390 --> 00:04:41.223
- I love it, I love it.

00:04:41.223 --> 00:04:43.900
- Or in degrading ranges of motion

00:04:43.900 --> 00:04:45.374
called diminishing range.

00:04:45.374 --> 00:04:47.002
And the effects,

00:04:47.002 --> 00:04:49.740
you basically need one set per body part.

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:52.330
That's what I did for a year

00:04:52.330 --> 00:04:53.310
when I prototyped it,

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:55.390
'cause even though I looked at the data,

00:04:55.390 --> 00:04:58.045
I thought this just really
seems too good to be true.

00:04:58.045 --> 00:05:02.230
I experimented with once
I got the prototype built,

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:05.440
oh I should say that at
first I was just gonna

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:08.123
write a book about ultra
heavy band training

00:05:08.123 --> 00:05:12.650
but go find somebody
that'll make you bands

00:05:12.650 --> 00:05:14.080
that will hold, two, three,

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:16.930
400, 500 pounds and train with the bands,

00:05:16.930 --> 00:05:18.382
the problem is a band,

00:05:18.382 --> 00:05:21.180
wants to be,

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:23.020
it wants to conform, right.

00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:25.240
So it stretches and it doesn't just,

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:27.150
it doesn't form a shape of a bar,

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:29.861
and so your wrists get twisted.

00:05:29.861 --> 00:05:32.655
And your ankles, if you're dead lifting

00:05:32.655 --> 00:05:36.302
with a 400 pound band,

00:05:36.302 --> 00:05:39.127
and stretch, your ankles
are bending inwards--

00:05:39.127 --> 00:05:40.026
- Oh hell yeah.

00:05:40.026 --> 00:05:42.210
- And your ankle does
not like lateral force.

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:43.043
- Right.

00:05:43.043 --> 00:05:45.360
- So what happens is you
have neural inhibition

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.821
which instantly starts
shutting muscle off.

00:05:47.821 --> 00:05:50.982
So when you're uncomfortable
when you're lifting something

00:05:50.982 --> 00:05:54.330
you're getting a crummy workout

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:58.831
or not one at all because muscles
are beginning to shut off.

00:05:58.831 --> 00:06:02.270
And so, within two days of experimenting

00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:03.103
with these heavy bands,

00:06:03.103 --> 00:06:04.970
I'm this is not gonna work.

00:06:04.970 --> 00:06:07.754
I gotta develop an Olympic bar which,

00:06:07.754 --> 00:06:10.250
so I can grab here and grab here

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:11.724
but I'm gonna do an overhead press

00:06:11.724 --> 00:06:15.135
where I can, it can rotate so,

00:06:15.135 --> 00:06:18.356
so the X3 is, it's an Olympic bar,

00:06:18.356 --> 00:06:20.557
full steel Olympic bar,

00:06:20.557 --> 00:06:22.120
I coated it in rubber,

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:23.180
a lot of people don't understand

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:25.928
that the whole thing is
actually tested the same spec,

00:06:25.928 --> 00:06:28.467
that a rogue, an Olympic bars which

00:06:28.467 --> 00:06:30.550
has some significant cost behind it

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:31.620
which people look at it and go

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:32.747
why is it so expensive.

00:06:32.747 --> 00:06:34.187
It's an orbit bar,

00:06:34.187 --> 00:06:39.187
and then the bands are not like
the goofy little rehab bands

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:40.965
that you can find at Walmart,

00:06:40.965 --> 00:06:44.991
these are hundreds of pounds at extension

00:06:44.991 --> 00:06:48.384
to deliver, not only are
you getting more force,

00:06:48.384 --> 00:06:52.292
but you're getting more force
at more repetitions, so--

00:06:52.292 --> 00:06:54.645
- And and and and at appropriate points

00:06:54.645 --> 00:06:56.967
in the muscle contraction

00:06:56.967 --> 00:06:59.653
and this is the
interesting thing about it.

